## Background Jobs & Message Queue

### BullMQ v5.69.4

**Components:**

- `bullmq`: ^5.69.4
- `@nestjs/bullmq`: ^11.0.4
- `@bull-board/api`: ^6.19.0 (dev - queue monitoring UI)
- `@bull-board/fastify`: ^6.19.0 (dev - Fastify adapter for Bull Board)

**Best Practices:**

- Use BullMQ for all async background processing
- Define job payloads in `libs/queue/src/interfaces/`
- Use `QueueProducerService` from `@lib/queue` for type-safe job dispatch
- Extend `AbstractProcessor` from `@lib/queue` for worker processors
- Keep job payloads serializable (no class instances)
- Use separate queues per domain (ai-processing, data-ingestion, entitlement-processing)
- Configure appropriate retry strategies and backoff

**Version Notes:**

- BullMQ v5 requires ioredis (not node-redis)
- @nestjs/bullmq v11 integrates with NestJS 11 DI
- Bull Board provides visual queue monitoring in development

**Architecture:**

- `libs/queue/` - Shared queue module, producer service, job interfaces
- `apps/api/` - Job producers (dispatch via QueueProducerService)
- `apps/worker-ai/` - AI processing consumer
- `apps/worker-ingestion/` - Data ingestion consumer
- `apps/api/src/modules/entitlements/processors/` - Entitlement async processing

### Redis (via ioredis v5.9.2)

**Components:**

- `ioredis`: ^5.9.2

**Best Practices:**

- Use ioredis (not node-redis) as required by BullMQ
- Connection management via `libs/redis/` module
- Use Redis health checks (`redis.health.ts`)
- Configure appropriate connection timeouts
- Use `appendonly yes` for persistence in Docker

**Version Notes:**

- ioredis v5 is the most popular Redis client for Node.js
- Full Redis command support with TypeScript types
- Built-in connection pooling and reconnection

**Architecture:**

- `libs/redis/` - Shared Redis module, service, health indicator
- Used as BullMQ backend for all queue operations
- Docker service: `redis:7-alpine` with AOF persistence

